00:13:17,638 --> 00:13:18,931
How long?

60
00:13:19,223 --> 00:13:21,475
Two years, four months, 18 days...

61
00:13:21,642 --> 00:13:22,851
...36 hours, 15 minutes.

62
00:13:23,185 --> 00:13:24,436
Any casualties?

63
00:13:24,978 --> 00:13:26,105
Casualties, ma'am?

64
00:13:26,272 --> 00:13:27,314
Has anyone died?

65
00:13:27,898 --> 00:13:29,817
No, ma'am. Everyone is fine.

66
00:13:31,902 --> 00:13:33,486
Well, then wake them up.

67
00:13:44,747 --> 00:13:46,667
Try to relax, Dr. Shaw.

68
00:13:47,876 --> 00:13:49,461
My name is David.

69
00:13:50,879 --> 00:13:53,215
Your mind and body
are in a state of shock...

70
00:13:53,382 --> 00:13:55,467
...as a result of the stasis.

71
00:13:55,718 --> 00:13:57,594
It's all right. Perfectly normal.

72
00:13:57,803 --> 00:13:58,636
Ellie.

73
00:13:59,846 --> 00:14:01,222
We're here, baby.

74
00:14:05,560 --> 00:14:06,395
There, there.

75
00:14:08,230 --> 00:14:10,480
Drink plenty of water.
Drink plenty of fluids.

76
00:14:11,983 --> 00:14:13,402
Hydration aids muscle mass.

77
00:14:18,573 --> 00:14:21,660
All crew, consume shakes
with high caloric content.

78
00:14:27,916 --> 00:14:30,084
What the hell is that?

79
00:14:32,170 --> 00:14:33,046
It's Christmas.

80
00:14:33,463 --> 00:14:34,613
We need the holidays...

81
00:14:34,756 --> 00:14:36,356
...to show time is still moving.

82
00:14:36,466 --> 00:14:37,416
Mission briefing...

83
00:14:37,550 --> 00:14:39,093
...is about to start, captain.

84
00:14:39,595 --> 00:14:41,180
Might wanna make your way down.

85
00:14:41,430 --> 00:14:43,765
Well, l haven't had any breakfast yet.

86
00:14:44,266 --> 00:14:45,642
Is this seat taken?

87
00:14:46,811 --> 00:14:49,396
Hi, l'm Millburn, Biology.
Nice to meet you.

88
00:14:51,607 --> 00:14:52,440
Okay.

89
00:14:52,524 --> 00:14:56,027
Look, no offense, but...

90
00:14:56,569 --> 00:14:58,613
...l've been asleep two years.

91
00:14:59,281 --> 00:15:01,825
I ain't here to be your friend.

92
00:15:02,159 --> 00:15:03,451
I'm here to make money.

93
00:15:04,577 --> 00:15:05,912
You got that?

94
00:15:08,457 --> 00:15:09,791
Okay.

95
00:15:10,125 --> 00:15:12,837
I bet a hundred credits
it's a terraforming survey.

96
00:15:13,004 --> 00:15:15,047
No, if it's a survey, they would tell us.

97
00:15:15,130 --> 00:15:17,466
It's a corporate run,
they're not telling us shit.

98
00:15:17,549 --> 00:15:18,383
Come on.

99
00:15:18,550 --> 00:15:20,469
- A hundred.
- All right, you're on.

100
00:15:25,139 --> 00:15:26,558
You look nervous, El.

101
00:15:27,142 --> 00:15:30,062
- L'll try to keep my feet on the ground.
- L know you will.

102
00:15:30,145 --> 00:15:31,062
Good morning.

103
00:15:31,813 --> 00:15:34,357
For those of you l hired personally...

104
00:15:35,358 --> 00:15:37,485
...it's nice to see you again.

105
00:15:38,277 --> 00:15:42,327
For the rest of you, l am Meredith Vickers.
It's my job to make sure you do yours.

106
00:15:42,657 --> 00:15:45,243
Okay, then. On with the show.

107
00:15:50,831 --> 00:15:52,582
Weyland Corporation.

108
00:15:52,834 --> 00:15:54,835
Building better worlds.

109
00:15:56,128 --> 00:15:57,713
Hello, friends.

110
00:15:59,674 --> 00:16:01,426
My name is Peter Weyland.

111
00:16:03,469 --> 00:16:05,262
I am your employer.

112
00:16:05,513 --> 00:16:10,560
I am recording this, 22 June, 2091.
And if you're watching it...

113
00:16:11,394 --> 00:16:13,521
...you have reached your destination.

114
00:16:14,188 --> 00:16:16,190
And l am long dead.

115
00:16:16,815 --> 00:16:18,775
May l rest in peace.

116
00:16:19,986 --> 00:16:23,155
There's a man sitting with you today.
His name is David.

117
00:16:23,322 --> 00:16:26,367
And he is the closest thing to a son
l will ever have.

118
00:16:26,659 --> 00:16:29,412
Unfortunately, he is not human.

119
00:16:29,745 --> 00:16:30,995
He will never grow old...

120
00:16:31,205 --> 00:16:33,083
...and he will never die.

121
00:16:34,042 --> 00:16:37,211
And yet he is unable to appreciate
these remarkable gifts...

122
00:16:37,378 --> 00:16:41,715
...for that would require the one thing
that David will never have.

123
00:16:41,924 --> 00:16:43,050
A soul.

124
00:16:44,051 --> 00:16:45,761
I have spent my entire...

125
00:16:46,011 --> 00:16:48,431
...lifetime contemplating the questions:

126
00:16:48,723 --> 00:16:50,224
Where do we come from?

127
00:16:50,558 --> 00:16:52,059
What is our purpose?

128
00:16:52,309 --> 00:16:53,728
What happens when we die?

129
00:16:54,437 --> 00:16:58,587
And l have found two people who convinced
me they're on the verge of answering them.

130
00:16:59,066 --> 00:17:02,028
Drs. Holloway and Shaw,
if you would please stand.

131
00:17:04,363 --> 00:17:06,613
As far as you're concerned,
they're in charge.

132
00:17:07,533 --> 00:17:12,120
The Titan Prometheus wanted to give
mankind equal footing with the gods...

133
00:17:12,287 --> 00:17:15,875
...and for that, he was cast from Olympus.

134
00:17:16,750 --> 00:17:21,589
Well, my friends,
the time has finally come for his return.

135
00:17:22,215 --> 00:17:23,174
Doctors, please.

136
00:17:27,512 --> 00:17:28,462
The floor is yours.

137
00:17:36,937 --> 00:17:38,939
Okay, wow.

138
00:17:39,106 --> 00:17:40,483
All right.

139
00:17:40,650 --> 00:17:42,500
I never had to follow a ghost before.

140
00:17:42,818 --> 00:17:44,862
Okay, let me show you why you guys...

141
00:17:45,070 --> 00:17:46,155
...are here.

142
00:17:53,621 --> 00:17:58,792
These are images of archeological digs
from all over the Earth.

143
00:17:58,959 --> 00:17:59,793
That's...

144
00:17:59,960 --> 00:18:03,338
...Egyptian, Mayan, Sumerian, Babylonian.

145
00:18:03,588 --> 00:18:06,383
That's Hawaiian there at the end,
then Mesopotamian.

146
00:18:06,633 --> 00:18:09,636
Now, this one here
is our most recent discovery.

147
00:18:09,803 --> 00:18:13,807
It's a 35,000-year-old cave painting
from the lsle of Skye in Scotland.

148
00:18:14,099 --> 00:18:18,311
These are ancient civilizations.
They were separated by centuries.

149
00:18:18,478 --> 00:18:21,565
They shared no contact with one another,
and yet...

150
00:18:25,402 --> 00:18:26,486
The same pictogram...

151
00:18:26,653 --> 00:18:30,281
...showing men worshipping giant beings,
pointing to the stars...

152
00:18:30,490 --> 00:18:33,452
...was discovered
at every last one of them.

153
00:18:33,994 --> 00:18:36,621
And the only galactic system
that matched...

154
00:18:37,664 --> 00:18:40,209
...was so far from Earth
that there's no way...

155
00:18:40,375 --> 00:18:44,504
...that these primitive, ancient civilizations
could have possibly known about it.

156
00:18:44,671 --> 00:18:46,172
But itjust so happens...

157
00:18:47,883 --> 00:18:49,218
...that that system...

158
00:18:50,677 --> 00:18:51,803
...has a sun...

159
00:18:52,846 --> 00:18:54,264
...a lot like ours.

160
00:18:55,348 --> 00:18:59,644
And, based on our long-range scans,
there seemed to be a planet.

161
00:19:01,062 --> 00:19:03,314
Just one planet with a moon...

162
00:19:03,523 --> 00:19:05,441
...capable of sustaining life.

163
00:19:06,860 --> 00:19:08,945
And we arrived there this morning.

164
00:19:11,197 --> 00:19:16,036
So you're saying we're here because of a map
you two kids found in a cave. ls that right?

165
00:19:17,329 --> 00:19:18,580
- No.
- Yeah.

166
00:19:20,874 --> 00:19:23,334
No. Not a map, an invitation.

167
00:19:23,501 --> 00:19:24,877
From who?

168
00:19:26,379 --> 00:19:28,131
We call them Engineers.

169
00:19:29,049 --> 00:19:30,550
Engineers?

170
00:19:30,717 --> 00:19:31,551
Do you mind...

171
00:19:32,594 --> 00:19:34,388
...telling us what they engineered?

172
00:19:36,390 --> 00:19:38,058
They engineered us.

173
00:19:40,811 --> 00:19:41,645
Bullshit.

174
00:19:43,856 --> 00:19:45,732
Okay, so do you...

175
00:19:45,899 --> 00:19:47,567
...have anything to back that up?

176
00:19:48,276 --> 00:19:50,176
Look, if you're willing to discount...

177
00:19:50,278 --> 00:19:52,128
...centuries of Darwinism, that's...

178
00:19:55,283 --> 00:19:56,283
But how do you know?

179
00:19:57,744 --> 00:19:59,078
I don't.

180
00:19:59,579 --> 00:20:01,706
But it's what l choose to believe.

181
00:20:29,608 --> 00:20:30,651
Doctors.

182
00:20:31,735 --> 00:20:35,782
Miss Vickers would like to have
a quick word before the adventure begins.

183
00:20:43,288 --> 00:20:44,247
Wow, nice place.

184
00:20:44,414 --> 00:20:48,544
It's actually a separate module
with its own self-contained life support.

185
00:20:49,003 --> 00:20:50,671
Air, food.

186
00:20:50,963 --> 00:20:54,550
Anything Miss Vickers would need
to survive a hostile environment.

187
00:20:54,801 --> 00:20:56,761
Okay, so she lives on a lifeboat.

188
00:20:56,927 --> 00:20:57,970
Yes.

189
00:20:58,137 --> 00:20:58,804
I do.

190
00:20:58,971 --> 00:21:01,224
I like to minimize risk.

191
00:21:01,808 --> 00:21:05,394
David, why don't you make
the doctors a drink?

192
00:21:05,978 --> 00:21:08,731
L'll take a vodka. Up.

193
00:21:09,148 --> 00:21:10,566
Charlie, look.

194
00:21:10,774 --> 00:21:13,109
It's a Pauling Med-Pod.

195
00:21:13,402 --> 00:21:15,780
They only made a dozen of these.

196
00:21:15,946 --> 00:21:16,780
Miss Shaw.

197
00:21:16,947 --> 00:21:19,408
Please verbally state
the nature of your injury.

198
00:21:19,866 --> 00:21:21,494
Please don't touch that.

199
00:21:21,661 --> 00:21:23,711
It's a very expensive piece of machinery.

200
00:21:24,163 --> 00:21:26,666
It does bypass surgery.
What do you need it for?

201
00:21:28,501 --> 00:21:31,128
There might be some confusion
about our relationship.

202
00:21:32,213 --> 00:21:35,013
Weyland found you impressive enough
to fund this mission.

203
00:21:35,215 --> 00:21:37,760
But l'm fairly certain your Engineers
are scribblings...

204
00:21:37,843 --> 00:21:40,054
...of savages living
in dirty little caves.

205
00:21:41,305 --> 00:21:44,605
But let's say l'm wrong,
and you do find these beings down there...

206
00:21:45,517 --> 00:21:47,645
...you won't engage them...

207
00:21:47,937 --> 00:21:49,438
...you won't talk to them.

208
00:21:49,689 --> 00:21:52,316
You will do nothing but report back to me.

209
00:21:55,862 --> 00:21:58,114
Miss Vickers, is there an agenda that...

210
00:21:58,281 --> 00:21:59,907
...you're not telling us about?

211
00:22:00,491 --> 00:22:01,158
My company...

212
00:22:01,325 --> 00:22:03,953
...paid a trillion dollars to
find this place and bring you.

213
00:22:04,036 --> 00:22:06,831
Had you raised the monies yourself,
Mr. Holloway...

214
00:22:06,998 --> 00:22:09,875
...we'd happily be pursuing your agenda.

215
00:22:11,210 --> 00:22:12,461
But you didn't.

216
00:22:12,878 --> 00:22:14,463
And that makes you an employee.

217
00:22:15,922 --> 00:22:17,924
But if we can't make contact...

218
00:22:18,091 --> 00:22:20,594
...why did you even bring us here?

219
00:22:21,386 --> 00:22:24,139
Weyland was a superstitious man.

220
00:22:24,848 --> 00:22:27,225
He wanted a true believer onboard.

221
00:22:29,894 --> 00:22:31,103
Cheers.

222
00:22:34,399 --> 00:22:35,567
So no response?

223
00:22:36,234 --> 00:22:37,318
I'm sorry, no.

224
00:22:37,485 --> 00:22:39,403
Maybe they didn't understand it.

225
00:22:40,781 --> 00:22:42,824
How are your lessons going, David?

226
00:22:44,034 --> 00:22:47,579
I spent two years deconstructing
dozens of ancient languages...

227
00:22:48,205 --> 00:22:49,915
...to their roots. l'm confident...

228
00:22:49,998 --> 00:22:51,648
...l can communicate with them...

229
00:22:51,750 --> 00:22:53,918
...provided your thesis is correct.

230
00:22:55,211 --> 00:22:57,338
"Provided it's correct." That's good.

231
00:22:57,505 --> 00:23:00,425
That's why they call it a thesis, doctor.

232
00:23:03,511 --> 00:23:05,221
What are you smiling about?

233
00:23:05,388 --> 00:23:07,266
Mr. Ravel, Mr. Chance, take her down.

234
00:23:07,432 --> 00:23:08,934
- Roger that.
- Yes, captain.

235
00:23:09,309 --> 00:23:10,769
Descent trajectory mapped.

236
00:23:11,102 --> 00:23:12,479
How we doing?

237
00:23:12,645 --> 00:23:13,731
Great.

238
00:23:14,982 --> 00:23:15,815
All right, boss.

239
00:23:16,441 --> 00:23:17,274
All personnel...

240
00:23:17,401 --> 00:23:18,568
...this is the captain.

241
00:23:18,735 --> 00:23:20,153
Brace for entry.

242
00:23:20,320 --> 00:23:21,571
Yes, captain.

243
00:23:22,113 --> 00:23:23,614
That means you too, Vickers.

244
00:23:23,781 --> 00:23:24,866
All systems...

245
00:23:25,116 --> 00:23:26,033
...online.

246
00:23:33,416 --> 00:23:34,668
What is the atmosphere?

247
00:23:34,835 --> 00:23:36,044
Atmosphere is...

248
00:23:36,211 --> 00:23:37,462
...71 percent nitrogen...

249
00:23:37,629 --> 00:23:38,797
...21 percent oxygen...

250
00:23:38,963 --> 00:23:40,113
...traces of argon gas.

251
00:23:40,299 --> 00:23:42,342
Whoa, now, that's weather.

252
00:23:42,551 --> 00:23:43,635
Just like home.

253
00:23:43,802 --> 00:23:45,952
If you're breathing
through an exhaust pipe.

254
00:23:46,137 --> 00:23:48,097
CO2 is over 3 percent.

255
00:23:48,264 --> 00:23:50,308
Two minutes without a suit, you're dead.

256
00:23:53,812 --> 00:23:54,938
Peak portside.

257
00:23:55,188 --> 00:23:56,940
Whoa, 52,000!

258
00:23:57,190 --> 00:23:59,317
It makes Everest look like a baby brother.

259
00:23:59,609 --> 00:24:01,820
All right, take us around.

260
00:24:01,987 --> 00:24:03,837
We'll use that as our point of entry.

261
00:24:06,157 --> 00:24:08,410
Terrain data rezzing up. We've got...

262
00:24:08,577 --> 00:24:09,995
...a couple of hard spots.

263
00:24:10,162 --> 00:24:11,663
Could be metal.

264
00:24:32,474 --> 00:24:33,724
No radio, no heat source.

265
00:24:34,769 --> 00:24:35,853
Nobody's home.

266
00:24:37,104 --> 00:24:38,754
There is nothing in the desert...

267
00:24:39,523 --> 00:24:41,191
...and no man needs nothing.

268
00:24:41,567 --> 00:24:42,776
What was that?

269
00:24:44,027 --> 00:24:46,112
Just something from a film l like.

270
00:24:50,451 --> 00:24:51,951
Let's go through that gateway.

271
00:24:52,160 --> 00:24:54,205
Reduce airspeed by a hundred knots.

272
00:24:58,876 --> 00:25:01,629
Going through. Nice and slow.

273
00:25:07,634 --> 00:25:08,719
Keep it steady, boys.

274
00:25:08,886 --> 00:25:09,719
There.

275
00:25:10,053 --> 00:25:11,721
No, what are you doing?

276
00:25:11,888 --> 00:25:14,767
Dr. Holloway, why don't you take a seat?

277
00:25:16,101 --> 00:25:18,020
Right there. God does not build in...

278
00:25:18,187 --> 00:25:21,315
...straight lines.
Starboard side, this valley! Captain...

279
00:25:21,482 --> 00:25:23,032
...could you put us down there?

280
00:25:23,192 --> 00:25:25,402
I wouldn't be any good
if l couldn't do that.

281
00:25:25,569 --> 00:25:28,906
Mr. Ravel, starboard 90 degrees.

282
00:25:33,786 --> 00:25:36,997
- One mile, port bow.
- One mile, port bow.

283
00:25:37,289 --> 00:25:38,915
Engage landing sequence.

284
00:25:39,082 --> 00:25:40,208
Switch to manual.

285
00:25:40,375 --> 00:25:41,627
- Commence landing.
- Easy.

286
00:25:41,710 --> 00:25:43,754
- Roger that.
- Yeah, baby, yeah.

287
00:25:46,548 --> 00:25:47,925
Bringing her down in five.

288
00:25:48,092 --> 00:25:49,885
- Preparing RCS thrusters.
- Four.

289
00:25:53,555 --> 00:25:55,266
Two. Easy does it.

290
00:26:12,908 --> 00:26:15,620
Generator systems are inactive.

291
00:26:15,786 --> 00:26:18,122
Temperature is at 2.724 K.

292
00:26:30,008 --> 00:26:31,058
Captain, would you...

293
00:26:31,218 --> 00:26:33,220
...tell the survey team to suit up...

294
00:26:33,386 --> 00:26:34,886
...and meet us in the airlock.

295
00:26:35,347 --> 00:26:37,141
Only six hours left of daylight.

296
00:26:37,307 --> 00:26:39,157
- Leave it till morning.
- No, no, no.

297
00:26:39,685 --> 00:26:41,144
It's Christmas, captain...

298
00:26:41,311 --> 00:26:43,188
...and l want to open my presents.

299
00:26:43,480 --> 00:26:44,314
You, boy.

300
00:26:44,481 --> 00:26:45,815
You're coming with us.

301
00:26:46,149 --> 00:26:47,609
L'd be delighted.

302
00:26:53,156 --> 00:26:55,783
Attention: Ramp will open in five minutes.

303
00:26:57,994 --> 00:26:59,578
Hey, Jackson...

304
00:26:59,954 --> 00:27:01,206
...what's that for?

305
00:27:01,998 --> 00:27:02,998
Expedition security.

306
00:27:03,166 --> 00:27:05,751
My job is to make sure
everybody is nice and safe.

307
00:27:07,337 --> 00:27:10,298
This is a scientific expedition.
No weapons.

308
00:27:10,465 --> 00:27:11,508
All right, then.

309
00:27:11,883 --> 00:27:13,259
Good luck with that.

310
00:27:16,221 --> 00:27:18,171
David, why are you wearing a suit, man?

311
00:27:19,516 --> 00:27:20,642
I beg your pardon?

312
00:27:20,808 --> 00:27:22,477
You don't breathe, remember?

313
00:27:22,643 --> 00:27:24,770
So why wear a suit?

314
00:27:25,396 --> 00:27:27,524
I was designed like this...

315
00:27:27,816 --> 00:27:31,903
...because you people are more comfortable
interacting with your own kind.

316
00:27:33,029 --> 00:27:36,366
If l didn't wear the suit,
it would defeat the purpose.

317
00:27:37,325 --> 00:27:39,425
They're making you guys pretty close, huh?

318
00:27:39,869 --> 00:27:41,330
Not too close, l hope.

319
00:27:51,172 --> 00:27:53,716
Attention: Ramp will open in 15 seconds.

320
00:27:59,096 --> 00:28:00,807
Ramp will open in five...

321
00:28:00,974 --> 00:28:05,019
...four, three, two, one.

322
00:28:22,454 --> 00:28:23,746
Hey.

323
00:28:24,455 --> 00:28:26,874
This is just one small step for mankind.

324
00:28:27,751 --> 00:28:28,752
Seriously?

325
00:28:34,925 --> 00:28:36,775
You ready to do this? l know you are.

326
00:28:47,394 --> 00:28:48,355
Hey, Fifield.

327
00:28:48,521 --> 00:28:49,815
I want a spectrograph on this.

328
00:28:49,898 --> 00:28:52,192
I want to know if it's natural
or if somebody put it there.

329
00:28:52,275 --> 00:28:55,028
I can't tell you if it's natural or not.
But what l can...

330
00:28:55,111 --> 00:28:57,237
...tell you is, it's hollow.

331
00:29:21,387 --> 00:29:25,140
Prometheus, are you seeing this?

332
00:29:25,474 --> 00:29:26,642
Affirmative.

333
00:29:26,975 --> 00:29:28,269
We see it.

334
00:29:35,484 --> 00:29:36,151
Okay, ready?

335
00:29:36,318 --> 00:29:37,819
- Yeah.
- Let's do it.

336
00:30:11,228 --> 00:30:13,396
- After you.
- After you.

337
00:30:13,522 --> 00:30:14,482
Okay.

338
00:30:14,649 --> 00:30:15,691
Careful.

339
00:30:16,358 --> 00:30:18,318
Prometheus, we're going in.

340
00:30:18,569 --> 00:30:19,695
Copy that.

341
00:30:53,228 --> 00:30:54,078
What's back here?

342
00:30:54,229 --> 00:30:56,356
Some kind of a corridor?

343
00:30:57,274 --> 00:30:59,859
Mr. Fifield,
let's get a grid of the structure.

344
00:31:00,026 --> 00:31:01,403
I want the whole interior.

345
00:31:02,404 --> 00:31:04,704
If there's anything in here
worth looking at...

346
00:31:04,865 --> 00:31:06,215
...these pups'll find them.

347
00:31:06,783 --> 00:31:07,742
"Pups"?

348
00:31:07,909 --> 00:31:10,245
Yeah, pups. My pups.

349
00:31:25,050 --> 00:31:27,804
Prometheus, we are now mapping.

350
00:31:32,099 --> 00:31:33,184
Copy that.

351
00:31:45,530 --> 00:31:46,580
Well, l'll be damned.

352
00:32:01,254 --> 00:32:02,505
Fifield, you got a read?

353
00:32:02,672 --> 00:32:03,798
Yeah.

354
00:32:04,549 --> 00:32:07,510
Pups are saying this way.

355
00:32:26,070 --> 00:32:27,488
Look at this.

356
00:32:34,830 --> 00:32:36,456
Oh, Charlie.

357
00:32:40,460 --> 00:32:41,502
Jesus.

358
00:32:41,836 --> 00:32:43,671
The sunlight is heating the water.

359
00:32:44,338 --> 00:32:45,923
Check out the humidity.

360
00:32:46,131 --> 00:32:47,781
Yeah, and look at the CO2 levels.

361
00:32:48,259 --> 00:32:49,302
Outside...

362
00:32:49,469 --> 00:32:51,512
...it's completely toxic, and in here...

363
00:32:51,679 --> 00:32:53,764
...there's nothing. lt's breathable.

364
00:32:55,850 --> 00:32:57,435
What are you doing?

365
00:32:57,602 --> 00:32:59,854
- Don't be an idiot.
- Don't be a skeptic.

366
00:33:00,396 --> 00:33:02,496
There's something
generating an atmosphere.

367
00:33:02,858 --> 00:33:04,109
David?

368
00:33:04,276 --> 00:33:06,528
- Dr. Holloway is correct.
- Cleaner than Earth...

369
00:33:06,611 --> 00:33:07,779
...actually.

370
00:33:07,946 --> 00:33:09,096
They were terraforming.

371
00:33:09,197 --> 00:33:10,656
Please don't do...

372
00:33:10,823 --> 00:33:12,658
l'm not wearing this thing anymore.

373
00:33:13,158 --> 00:33:14,410
Wish me luck, baby.

374
00:33:14,661 --> 00:33:17,205
Do you copy?
Do not remove your headgear.

375
00:33:33,804 --> 00:33:35,722
You crazy bastard.

376
00:33:40,393 --> 00:33:41,729
Connect our suit cameras...

377
00:33:41,812 --> 00:33:46,066
...if you want to continue watching this
freak show. We are taking our helmets off.

378
00:33:47,192 --> 00:33:48,903
Copy that. Switching feeds.

379
00:33:50,904 --> 00:33:53,073
Well, come on. Pay up.

380
00:33:53,782 --> 00:33:56,494
- Pay what?
- What do you mean, "Pay what"?

381
00:33:56,660 --> 00:34:00,164
Something is manufacturing
breathable air down there. That, mate...

382
00:34:00,330 --> 00:34:03,167
- ...is terraforming.
- No, no. The bet was why we came here.

383
00:34:03,250 --> 00:34:06,211
If you said a dead old man wanted
to talk to Martians, l'd pay.

384
00:34:06,294 --> 00:34:07,670
Come on, a hundred credits.

385
00:34:07,837 --> 00:34:10,841
Put it towards a lap dance with
Miss Vickers. How about that?

386
00:34:12,926 --> 00:34:15,096
It's minus 12 in here.

387
00:34:15,262 --> 00:34:17,389
So why is this water not frozen?

388
00:34:17,556 --> 00:34:18,974
Maybe it ain't water.

389
00:34:19,725 --> 00:34:21,184
Maybe it's Martian piss.

390
00:34:23,229 --> 00:34:26,273
That's your scientific theory?

391
00:34:26,440 --> 00:34:28,358
Is it? Mr. Biology?

392
00:34:32,570 --> 00:34:34,520
Whatever it is, it sure is collagenous.

393
00:34:35,574 --> 00:34:37,284
Some kind of sediment, perhaps.

394
00:34:57,304 --> 00:34:58,430
Impressive.

395
00:35:18,159 --> 00:35:18,992
What was that?

396
00:35:19,827 --> 00:35:21,036
David?

397
00:35:21,954 --> 00:35:22,787
David?

398
00:35:24,039 --> 00:35:25,248
What is that?

399
00:35:27,250 --> 00:35:28,168
David?

400
00:35:36,843 --> 00:35:38,136
Ellie!

401
00:35:43,016 --> 00:35:43,850
What was that?

402
00:35:44,642 --> 00:35:46,603
I'm really glad we didn't bring weapons.

403
00:35:46,686 --> 00:35:48,986
- Come on, El. Let's go.
- Whose idea was that?

404
00:35:49,397 --> 00:35:50,314
Keep up!

405
00:35:52,775 --> 00:35:53,608
Come on!

406
00:36:01,408 --> 00:36:02,744
Where did he go?

407
00:36:08,040 --> 00:36:09,626
Wait, wait, wait.

408
00:36:14,589 --> 00:36:17,675
There it is. There it is. There it is.

409
00:36:18,676 --> 00:36:21,178
Oh, my God, Charlie. We found them.

410
00:36:21,345 --> 00:36:22,889
What do you mean "them"?

411
00:36:24,182 --> 00:36:25,599
It is them, Ellie.

412
00:36:26,392 --> 00:36:27,977
It looks like a door...

413
00:36:28,353 --> 00:36:32,315
...and he's been decapitated by it.

414
00:36:33,566 --> 00:36:35,068
Son of a bitch.

415
00:36:36,820 --> 00:36:38,196
They were right.

416
00:36:41,699 --> 00:36:43,784
What did you want them to be? Wrong?

417
00:36:47,579 --> 00:36:48,706
David...

418
00:36:49,415 --> 00:36:51,215
...please tell me you can read that.

419
00:36:51,751 --> 00:36:53,002
Perhaps.

420
00:36:55,255 --> 00:36:56,923
No, l'm out of here.

421
00:36:58,925 --> 00:37:00,760
Hey, Fifield, where are you going?

422
00:37:02,429 --> 00:37:03,513
What?

423
00:37:05,265 --> 00:37:07,934
Look, l'm just a geologist.

424
00:37:08,101 --> 00:37:10,269
I like rocks. l love rocks!

425
00:37:10,728 --> 00:37:13,272
Now it's clear
you two don't give a shit about rocks.

426
00:37:13,355 --> 00:37:16,005
But what you do seem to care about
is gigantic dead...

427
00:37:16,109 --> 00:37:16,942
...bodies.

428
00:37:17,026 --> 00:37:20,113
As l don't really have anything
to contribute in the gigantic...

429
00:37:20,196 --> 00:37:21,614
...dead body arena...

430
00:37:23,158 --> 00:37:26,661
...l want to go back to the ship,
if you don't mind.

431
00:37:30,123 --> 00:37:30,956
Anyone wanna...

432
00:37:31,041 --> 00:37:33,167
...join me, hey? You staying?

433
00:37:34,877 --> 00:37:35,920
No, ship's good.

434
00:37:36,087 --> 00:37:38,297
Yeah. Ship very good.

435
00:37:39,256 --> 00:37:42,302
Congratulations on meeting your maker.

436
00:37:43,094 --> 00:37:44,262
Thank you.

437
00:37:44,971 --> 00:37:45,804
Pull yourself...

438
00:37:45,888 --> 00:37:46,806
...together, man.

439
00:37:50,267 --> 00:37:53,228
And l thought you were the crazy one.

440
00:38:01,111 --> 00:38:02,904
Do you have the carbon reader?

441
00:38:05,323 --> 00:38:06,616
Thank you.

442
00:38:12,831 --> 00:38:14,031
How long's it been dead?

443
00:38:16,752 --> 00:38:17,836
Two thousand years...

444
00:38:18,003 --> 00:38:19,171
...give or take.

445
00:38:22,758 --> 00:38:24,343
What are you doing, David?

446
00:38:25,302 --> 00:38:27,012
I'm attempting to open the door.

447
00:38:27,179 --> 00:38:29,472
Wait. We don't know
what's on the other side.

448
00:38:31,850 --> 00:38:33,268
Oops. Sorry.

449
00:38:37,939 --> 00:38:40,275
Look, Ford. lt's the head.

450
00:38:50,786 --> 00:38:53,038
An amazing state of preservation.

451
00:38:53,330 --> 00:38:55,082
- We'll take it in.
- Yeah.

452
00:38:59,169 --> 00:39:00,712
Remarkably human.

453
00:39:18,397 --> 00:39:20,065
Beautiful painting.

454
00:39:21,191 --> 00:39:22,484
It's a mural.

455
00:39:35,079 --> 00:39:35,748
Stop.

456
00:39:35,915 --> 00:39:37,082
Stop. Don't touch it.

457
00:39:37,249 --> 00:39:38,333
Sorry.

458
00:39:39,501 --> 00:39:41,461
Please, don't touch anything.

459
00:39:42,421 --> 00:39:43,254
Sweating.

460
00:40:22,043 --> 00:40:23,211
Organic.

461
00:40:29,801 --> 00:40:30,802
Oh, no.

462
00:40:31,094 --> 00:40:33,804
Charlie, the murals are changing.

463
00:40:33,971 --> 00:40:36,421
I think we've affected the atmosphere
in the room.

464
00:40:36,599 --> 00:40:38,434
Charlie, do you copy?

465
00:40:39,477 --> 00:40:40,311
Oh, the head!

466
00:40:40,603 --> 00:40:42,688
Ford, quick, help me bag the head!

467
00:40:54,325 --> 00:40:55,827
- Boss.
- What you got?

468
00:40:56,828 --> 00:40:58,746
We got an incoming storm front.

469
00:40:58,913 --> 00:41:00,081
Silica...

470
00:41:00,247 --> 00:41:02,250
...and lots of static. This is not good.

471
00:41:02,417 --> 00:41:03,250
I see it.

472
00:41:07,255 --> 00:41:08,089
Ground crew...

473
00:41:08,297 --> 00:41:09,298
...this is Janek.

474
00:41:09,465 --> 00:41:11,300
I need you to hustle back right now.

475
00:41:11,592 --> 00:41:13,093
Ground crew, do you copy me?

476
00:41:13,302 --> 00:41:14,595
I got 200-kilometer...

477
00:41:14,761 --> 00:41:16,347
...winds of airborne silica...

478
00:41:16,472 --> 00:41:18,057
...and enough static to fry your suit.

479
00:41:18,140 --> 00:41:19,642
Copy that, sir.

480
00:41:19,808 --> 00:41:20,768
We need more time.

481
00:41:21,477 --> 00:41:22,877
L'll be closing the outer...

482
00:41:22,979 --> 00:41:24,188
...doors in 15 minutes.

483
00:41:24,355 --> 00:41:26,524
I sincerely hope you can make it.

484
00:41:29,277 --> 00:41:31,196
Charlie! David!

485
00:41:31,779 --> 00:41:32,864
We must leave now.

486
00:41:35,032 --> 00:41:36,700
This is just another tomb.

487
00:41:41,204 --> 00:41:42,415
David!

488
00:41:45,292 --> 00:41:47,169
- On three.
- Two, three, up.

489
00:41:47,336 --> 00:41:48,712
Let's go!

490
00:41:49,464 --> 00:41:51,215
Easy, easy, easy. Careful.

491
00:41:54,301 --> 00:41:57,013
David, we are leaving!

492
00:42:06,563 --> 00:42:07,397
Come on!

493
00:42:07,564 --> 00:42:09,314
Damn it, they've already taken off.

494
00:42:09,442 --> 00:42:10,401
Come on, let's go.

495
00:42:12,069 --> 00:42:15,197
Prometheus to ground crew.
You're running out of time.

496
00:42:15,406 --> 00:42:17,407
All right, come on. Let's go.

497
00:42:32,714 --> 00:42:34,090
Go faster!

498
00:42:57,947 --> 00:42:59,073
Charlie! The head!

499
00:43:00,074 --> 00:43:00,616
Ellie, no!

500
00:43:00,783 --> 00:43:01,733
What are you doing?

501
00:43:10,252 --> 00:43:11,085
Hatch closure...

502
00:43:11,211 --> 00:43:12,611
- ...in five seconds.
- Shit.

503
00:43:13,505 --> 00:43:14,355
Damn it, hold on!

504
00:43:16,634 --> 00:43:17,467
Goddamn it.

505
00:43:17,593 --> 00:43:18,719
Door closing.

506
00:43:20,929 --> 00:43:22,013
Ellie, don't move!

507
00:43:27,226 --> 00:43:28,059
Charlie!

508
00:43:31,439 --> 00:43:32,482
Grab my hand!

509
00:43:43,661 --> 00:43:44,494
No!

510
00:43:45,204 --> 00:43:46,121
No, Ellie!

511
00:43:46,288 --> 00:43:47,121
Ellie!

512
00:44:25,368 --> 00:44:26,369
Got it.

513
00:44:34,335 --> 00:44:36,171
So, what was that, Ellie?

514
00:44:36,463 --> 00:44:38,965
You could've compromised the mission.
Not to mention...

515
00:44:39,048 --> 00:44:40,508
...almost killing yourself!

516
00:44:40,675 --> 00:44:41,675
Are you all right?

517
00:44:42,093 --> 00:44:43,427
Yes.

518
00:44:43,719 --> 00:44:44,887
Thank you, David.

519
00:44:45,387 --> 00:44:46,888
My pleasure.

520
00:44:47,222 --> 00:44:49,015
Doctors, it's real good to have...

521
00:44:49,225 --> 00:44:51,519
...you back,
but where's Millburn and Fifield?

522
00:44:51,685 --> 00:44:53,395
Aren't they back yet?

523
00:44:54,897 --> 00:44:56,547
- Get them up for me.
- All right.

524
00:44:59,360 --> 00:45:01,070
We've been here before, Fifield.

525
00:45:01,237 --> 00:45:03,907
I don't know. lt all looks the same to me.

526
00:45:04,866 --> 00:45:06,909
Boys, this is the captain. Listen up.

527
00:45:07,535 --> 00:45:10,246
Between the static electricity
and the wind speed...

528
00:45:10,412 --> 00:45:12,812
...well, there ain't no safe way
to come get you.

529
00:45:13,332 --> 00:45:14,165
What?

530
00:45:14,249 --> 00:45:17,999
The temperature is dropping rapidly,
so get your helmets on and stay warm...

531
00:45:18,420 --> 00:45:20,422
...until the storm passes.

532
00:45:20,589 --> 00:45:21,423
Captain...

533
00:45:21,757 --> 00:45:25,107
...can you get a message to the scientist
and his zealot girlfriend?

534
00:45:26,095 --> 00:45:27,145
You got a pen nearby?

535
00:45:27,304 --> 00:45:29,223
No. No, l think we got it.

536
00:45:29,891 --> 00:45:31,726
Tell them l said... themselves.

537
00:45:32,977 --> 00:45:33,810
Copy?

538
00:45:33,978 --> 00:45:36,272
Copy that.
All right, boys, keep your head down...

539
00:45:36,355 --> 00:45:38,649
...and we'll come get you in the morning.

540
00:45:40,400 --> 00:45:41,401
Well, which way now?

541
00:45:41,568 --> 00:45:42,401
All right.

542
00:45:42,527 --> 00:45:44,572
Well, which way, huh?

543
00:45:58,544 --> 00:46:00,546
